This is a list of [[song]]s about the [[Cold War]]. * "[[19 (song)|19]]" by [[Paul Hardcastle]] *"[[1999 (Prince song)|1999]]" by Prince - "Yeah, everybody's got a bomb, We could all die any day" - referring to nuclear proliferation. * "[[2 Minutes to Midnight]]" by [[Iron Maiden]] – refers to the [[Doomsday Clock]], the symbolic clock used by the [[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]. In September 1953 the clock reached 23:58, the closest the clock ever got to midnight. This occurred when the United States and Soviet Union tested [[H-bomb]]s within nine months of one another. * "[[99 Luftballons]]" by German singer [[Nena]] – the song imagines a world where the release of 99 balloons triggers governments to scramble fighter jets to intercept them, ultimately leading to total nuclear annihilation. * "[[A Great Day for Freedom]]" * "[[A Hard Rain's a-Gonna Fall]]" by [[Bob Dylan]] - widely interpreted by reference to the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], even though it was written before that date (1962). * "[[Back in the USSR]]" by [[the Beatles]] - expresses the singer's great happiness on returning home to the USSR from the United States; political observers saw it as pro-Soviet. * "[[Balls to the Wall (song)|Balls to the Wall]]" – about human rights. * "Be Not Always", a 1984 song from The Jacksons' ''[[Victory (The Jacksons album)|Victory]]'' LP * "[[Bonzo Goes to Bitburg]]" – written in reaction to the visit paid by U.S. president Ronald Reagan to a military cemetery in Bitburg, West Germany, on May 5, 1985 * "[[Breathing (Kate Bush song)|Breathing]]" by [[Kate Bush]] – about a foetus aware of what is going on outside the womb and frightened by nuclear fallout, which implies that the song is set either during a nuclear war scare or a post-apocalyptic birth * "[[Bullet the Blue Sky]]" – originally written about the United States' military intervention during the 1980s in the [[Salvadoran Civil War]] * "[[Burning Heart (song)|Burning Heart]]" – the East versus West conflict is reflected by the fight in the boxing ring between [[Rocky Balboa|Rocky]] and [[Ivan Drago]] * "[[Christmas at Ground Zero]]" by [["Weird Al" Yankovic]] * "[[Crazy Train]]" by [[Ozzy Osbourne]] – main theme of the song is criticism of Cold War. * "[[Cult of Personality (song)|Cult of Personality]]" by [[Living Colour]] * "[[Dancing with Tears in My Eyes]]" by [[Ultravox]] * "Defcon" by Impakt ([[Dunk Yer Funk Records]]) * "[[Der Kommissar (song)|Der Kommissar]]" by [[Falco (musician)|Falco]] * "[[Dominion/Mother Russia]]" * "[[Eighties (song)|Eighties]]" by [[Killing Joke]] *"[[Epitaph (song)|Epitaph]]" by [[King Crimson]] * "[[Eve of Destruction (song)|Eve of Destruction]]" * "[[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]" by [[Tears for Fears]] * "[[Everyday Is Like Sunday]]" * "[[Fireworks (The Tragically Hip song)|Fireworks]]" by [[The Tragically Hip]] - set in 1972 in Canada and Russia, it references the [[Summit Series|Canada–USSR hockey series]], "crisis in the Kremlin," nationalism, and the "fake Cold War." * "[[Forever Young (Alphaville song)|Forever Young]]" by [[Alphaville (band)|Alphaville]] * "[[Fortunate Son]]" by [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] - discusses the sons of "fortunate" men in America who avoided the draft to Vietnam thanks to their family's wealth or prestige. * "[[Games Without Frontiers (song)|Games Without Frontiers]]" * "[[Goodnight Saigon]]" - about the [[Vietnam War]]. * "[[God, Country and My Baby]]" is a 1961 song written by John Dolan and performed by [[Johnny Burnette]]. * "Great Atomic Power" by [[Charlie Louvin]] - using the fear that nuclear bombs could wipe out the world to invoke repentance. * "[[Hammer to Fall]]" *"[[Hello Vietnam]]" written by Tom T. Hall and recorded by Johnnie Wright, 1965 * "[[Heresy (Rush song)|Heresy]]" by [[Rush (band)|Rush]] * "[[Heroes (David Bowie song)|Heroes]]" by [[David Bowie]] – a love song depicting lovers kissing "by the wall"; many songs from Bowie's "[[Berlin Trilogy]]" albums invoke themes of the Cold War, as they were recorded in [[West Berlin]]. * "[[Hiroshima (song)|Hiroshima]]" * "[[Holidays in the Sun (song)|Holidays in the Sun]]" by the [[Sex Pistols]] * "[[I Won't Let the Sun Go Down on Me]]" by [[Nik Kershaw]] * "[[It's a Mistake]]" by [[Men at Work]] * "[[Land of Confusion]]" by [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] * "[[Lawyers, Guns and Money]]" * "[[Leningrad (song)|Leningrad]]" by [[Billy Joel]] * "[[Morning Dew]]" * "Mutually Assured Destruction" by [[Gillan (band)|Gillan]] * "[[New Frontier (song)]]" by [[Donald Fagen]] * "[[Nikita (song)|Nikita]]" – a love song set against the East German border: the singer describes his crush on a beautiful border guard whom he cannot meet because he is not allowed into the country. * "[[Nuku pommiin]]" * "[[New Year's Day (U2 song)|New Year's Day]]" by [[U2]] * "[[Oh Moscow]]" * "[[Ordinary People (The Box song)|Ordinary People]]" - 1987 - A Canadian pop rock song by '''The Box''<nowiki/>' drawing contrasts between life in USA and USSR. * "[[Party at Ground Zero]]" * "[[Radio Free Europe (song)|Radio Free Europe]]" by [[R.E.M.]] * "[[Ready or Not (Bananarama song)|Ready or Not]]" by [[Bananarama]], about escaping over the Berlin Wall to reunite with lover * "[[The Inner Sanctum|Red Star Falling]]" by [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] * "Renegade" by [[Steppenwolf (band)|Steppenwolf]] * "[[Right Here, Right Now (Jesus Jones song)|Right Here, Right Now]]" by Jesus Jones * "[[Ronnie – Talk To Russia!]]" – cover says "Featuring Ronald Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev" * "[[Russians (song)|Russians]]" by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] - about hoping the "Russians love their children too" because that could be the only thing to save them from destruction if the East and West keep provoking each other * "[[Seconds (song)]] by U2" * “[[Since Yesterday]]” by [[Strawberry Switchblade]] * "So Long Mom (A Song For World War III)", by [[Tom Lehrer]] * “Soviet Snow”, by [[Shona Laing]] * "[[State of the Nation (Industry song)|State of the Nation]]" by [[Industry]] * "Strange Frontier" by [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] on his [[Strange Frontier]] album; the song was included on the [[Greenpeace – The Album|Greenpeace Non-Toxic Video Hits]] VHS and Laserdisc compilation *"[[Stranger in Moscow]]" by [[Michael Jackson]] * * "[[Subterraneans]]" * "[[The Fletcher Memorial Home]]" * "[[The Tide Is Turning]]" by [[Roger Waters]] * "[[The Visitors (song)|The Visitors]]" by [[ABBA]] * "[[The Wall (Steppenwolf song)|The Wall]]" by [[Steppenwolf (band)|Steppenwolf]] * "This Cold War With You" by [[Floyd Tillman]] * "[[Two Tribes]]" by [[Frankie Goes to Hollywood]] * "[[Two Suns in the Sunset]]" by [[Pink Floyd]] * "[[Washington Bullets]]" by [[The Clash]] - from the [[Sandanista!]] album (a reference to the [[Sandanista|communist rebel group in Nicaragua]]), the song condemns American anti-communist military activity in Latin America, ending with criticism of other major superpowers during the era * "[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]" by [[Billy Joel]] - a cleverly structured list of historical events of the Cold War period from the 1950s-1980s * "[[Weeping Wall (instrumental)|Weeping Wall]]" by [[David Bowie]] – described by Bowie as intending to evoke the misery of the [[Berlin Wall]] (see the description of [["Heroes" (David Bowie song)|Heroes]] above) * "[[West of the Wall]]" is a 1962 song written by [[Wayne Shanklin]], which was recorded as a single by [[Toni Fisher]]. * "[[When the Wind Blows (song)|When the Wind Blows]]" also by [[David Bowie]] * "[[White Train(song)|White Train]]" by [[Bananarama]], about the train that carried nuclear missiles across the US * "[[Wind of Change (Scorpions song)|Wind of Change]]" by [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]]
[[Category:Lists of songs about a topic|Cold War]] [[Category:Cold War in popular culture]]
